{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.21,0.03,0.07,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5255"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77467"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5255"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77467"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman visits the general practitioner with a two week history of lower back pain. It is sharp in nature and radiates to the back of her right leg, and sometimes causes numbness around her buttocks and inner thighs. She also mentions difficulty urinating but does not have any urinary or faecal incontinence. Her history includes breast cancer treated three years ago with radiation and mastectomy. She currently takes anastrozole. There is no history of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood pressure is 130/70mmHg, pulse 80/min, respiratory rate 12/min and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination of her upper limbs is normal. The power is 5/5 in the left lower limb and 3/5 in the right lower limb. Knee and ankle reflexes are +1 on the right lower limb and +2 on the left lower limb. A digital rectal examination finds a normal resting anal tone but reduced anal sphincter squeeze tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cauda equina syndrome","Conus medullaris syndrome","Central cord syndrome","Brown-Sequard syndrome","Anterior spinal cord syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECauda equina syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. This condition is a surgical emergency that develops with spinal cord compression below the L2 vertebral level. It can be caused by disc herniation or any pathology that compresses the spinal cord (e.g. tumour, trauma). It is characterised by the progressive development of saddle anaesthesia, bladder dysfunction, decreased anal tone. There can also be reduced lower limb reflexes, and back pain radiating to the lower limbs, which is associated with spinal canal stenosis. The patient\u0027s presentation of decreased anal tone and history of breast cancer raises the risk and likelihood of cauda equina syndrome and spinal metastases needs to be ruled out with a lumbar/sacral spine MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConus medullaris syndrome (CMS)\u003C/strong\u003E usually manifests with a sudden onset of lower back pain radiating to the lower limbs, distal sensory loss, urinary incontinence, and perianal numbness. It is caused by damage to the spinal cord at the T12-L2 vertebral levels, usually due to trauma, and patients typically report symmetric weakness in the distal limbs. Although CMS presents with perianal paraesthesia, it does not cause saddle anaesthesia which involves loss of sensation to the medial thighs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral cord syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis a condition involving injury to the central region of the spinal cord, affecting both the corticospinal and spinothalamic tracts. Hyperextension injury is the most common cause of this injury, usually from a car crash, but other aetiologies such as syringomyelia and spinal cord compression can contribute to this condition as well. Patients present with bilateral paresis where the upper limbs are more affected than the lower limbs, which is not consistent with the symptoms experienced by the patient in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrown-Sequard syndrome, \u003C/strong\u003Eor hemisection syndrome, refers to the hemisection of the cord with a lesion at the right or left half of the spinal cord. It is commonly caused by trauma (penetrating/crush injuries) but can also be caused by disc herniation, spinal epidural haematoma, or a tumour. This condition is characterised by ipsilateral loss of all sensation at the level of the lesion, ipsilateral loss of proprioception below the level of the lesion, and contralateral loss of pain and temperature sensation one or two levels below the lesion. As there was no loss of sensation or loss of pain/temperature sensation in the patient above, this option is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior spinal cord syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition caused by reduced blood flow to the anterior segment of the spinal cord via the anterior spinal artery, resulting in ischemic injury to the corticospinal and spinothalamic tracts. Patients usually present with bilateral loss of motor function and decreased pain and temperature sensation below the level of the lesion. However, this patient only has symptoms with a symmetric distribution, ruling out this option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cauda equina syndrome is characterised by progressive development of saddle anaesthesia, decreased anal tone, and bladder/bowel dysfunction.","Early recognition and surgical intervention are crucial in cauda equina syndrome to prevent permanent neurological damage."],"references":["Fraser S, Roberts L, Murphy E. Cauda equina syndrome: a literature review of its definition and clinical presentation. Arch Phys Med Rehabil. 2009 Nov;90(11):1964-8. doi: 10.1016/j.apmr.2009.03.021. PMID: 19887225. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19887225/","Shapiro S. Cauda equina syndrome secondary to lumbar disc herniation. Neurosurgery. 1993 May;32(5):743-6; discussion 746-7. doi: 10.1227/00006123-199305000-00007. PMID: 8492849. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8492849/","Miller J, West J, Khawar H, Middleton R. Cauda equina syndrome. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2023 Dec 5;84(11):1-7. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2023.0012. PMID: 38186331. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38186331/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T08:41:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T08:41:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5255"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77467"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"